<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Mirror cracks as the Left regards
its voters - A look at the fallout from a fourth election defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE tedious, acrimonious and wholly irrelevant row over who exactly was
responsible for what during Labour's election campaign is acting like a
lorry load of sand delivered to the party's Walworth Road headquarters.
As the 32-member national executive committee gathers to conduct its
election post mortem today, there is every danger that it will take the
ostrich option and bury its head in it. At the centre of the row is the role
played by Labour's Shadow Communications Agency - its polling, advertising
and image-making arm - and other sundry political advisers drafted in for
the campaign.
As the game of pass the parcel has speeded up, a leaked report by Mr Jim
Parish, a key organiser, has attributed many of the failures of the campaign
to the 'wholesale takeover' of day-to-day strategy by this unelected
inner-core group.
That the SCA, headed by Mr Phillip Gould, and others such as Ms Patricia
Hewitt, a former Kinnock aide, played a central role in the conduct of
election is indisputable. It is arguable, too, that the more worldly
experience of professional politicians might have been brought more heavily
to bear.
But all that does not mesh well with the conclusion of party workers on the
morning of April 9 that Labour had surpassed even its 1987 effort and fought
its best campaign ever.
To his credit, Mr Larry Whitty, the party's general secretary, has been
scrupulous in refusing to join the search for scapegoats. His official
report eschews all buck-passing and tells a more convincing story.
Far more significant than the role of the SCA, the Jennifer's Ear affair,
the Sheffield rally or Mr John Smith's tax plans was the 'general distrust'
felt by voters of the party and its leadership.
The report goes on to show an extraordinary haemorraging of support for
Labour in the last few days of the campaign. On the important 'economic
competence' question, for example, Labour saw its position slip from about
even with the Conservatives to an 18 percentage point deficit in the last
three days alone.
A post-election, qualitative survey of 'swing' voter groups appears to have
borne that out. Its findings were that Labour was regarded as old-fashioned,
tied to the past, and unduly linked to minority interests, not least the
trade unions.
But as this research was conducted by the widely disparaged SCA, some NEC
members, such as Ms Clare Short MP, have cast doubt on its veracity. 'They
would say that, wouldn't they,' she commented on Tuesday.
Yet other senior party figures also broadly subscribe to Mr Whitty's
alarming view that it is the product itself - not the promotional glitz -
that remains Labour's core problem. Mr David Hill, the party's
communications chief, in his own paper to the NEC agrees with Mr Neil
Kinnock himself that it is the historical baggage left over from the 1970s
and 1980s that continues to undermine Labour's election chances.
Many new Labour MPs concur that it is indeed that public image - Labour's
very identity - that is the central question.
In a cogent newspaper article this month, Mr Tony Wright, MP for Cannock,
has said that the party must now tackle the traditional no-go areas. It must
dump its 'ancestral commitment to a publicly owned economy', acknowledge a
new European social democratic identity and confront head-on a wholesale
reform of its constitution.
However, he appears dubious as to whether that is really achievable. 'In a
remarkable transformation,' he wrote, 'as the Conservatives have acquired a
radical identity, so Labour has become the conservative party.'
Today's NEC's inquest coincides with the publication of the first
comprehensive study of Labour's activists. To the surprise of some, this
analysis of more than 5,000 party members has found some remarkable
disparities between Labour members and voters.
Of the former, for example, some 75 per cent are owner-occupiers and nearly
half are designated of the 'salariat' - against 14 per cent of Labour voters
 -with just 26 described as working class (57).
Similarly, there is clear confirmation that the party's vanguard stands well
to the left of Labour voters on a number of important issues. On public
ownership, some 71 per cent of members believe in more nationalisation,
against 38 per cent of Labour voters.
If, as the authors Mr Patrick Seyd and Mr Paul Whiteley conclude, the
membership is 'socially unrepresentative' of Labour voters in significant
ways, how much more are its views politically unrepresentative of the
country as a whole?
Both Mr Whitty's and Mr Wright's analyses appear tacitly to acknowledge, if
not publicly endorse, the voters' perception of the party as both outdated
and out of touch.
There are no guarantees the predominately salaried, middle-aged, home-owning
and male arch-activists meeting today on the NEC will agree.
With Labour's leadership election firmly focused on party members as opposed
to the voters' at large, a radical debate has been shut down and old
prejudices reinforced - at least until the contest's conclusion on July 18.
As Mr Bryan Gould, candidate for both leader and deputy leader, put it in a
bitter speech this week, Labour's election inquest is in danger of becoming
'hunt the scapegoat'.
'If winning inner party elections becomes more important than devising ways
of winning general elections,' he said, 'Labour is in deep trouble.' The
danger is that to win the former, candidates must make their pitch to an
electorate whose views bear little relation to those of the voters' at
large.
Labour's Grass Roots by Patrick Seyd and Paul Whiteley, Clarendon Press,
Oxford Pounds 32.50.
</TEXT>
