<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour poll row flares again
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE open warfare over responsibility for Labour's election defeat flared
again last night when Mr John Prescott repeated claims that the campaign had
been hijacked by outsiders.
The transport spokesman's charges were described as 'complete rubbish' by Mr
Jack Cunningham, the party's campaigns co-ordinator.
Mr Prescott, in his criticism of the campaign, complained that despite being
a member of the shadow cabinet and the NEC he had to 'peer in on television
to see who was on the campaign strategy team and who was making decisions'.
But Dr Cunningham hit back in an interview immediately afterwards, saying:
'It comes ill from people who were a member of two, or even all three, of
those bodies to say now they didn't know what strategy was being laid down.'
He insisted there were regular presentations to the shadow cabinet, the
campaign strategy committee and to the NEC for months before the general
election.
He added: 'At all times in the campaign the decisions were taken in the
campaign management team which I chaired, and to suggest that a small group
of people tried to subvert or circumvent those decisions is complete
rubbish.'
Ms Patricia Hewitt, a former aide to Mr Neil Kinnock, also counter-attacked
against the 'huge cowardice' of people refusing to take responsibility for
collective leadership decisions.
Last night, Mr Stan Orme, Labour MP for Salford East, announced that he
would not be seeking re-election as chairman of the parliamentary Labour
party.
</TEXT>
