<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Funds to charities remain stable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TYPICAL support for charity averaged Pounds 2 a person a month in 1990-91,
according to research published by the Charities Aid Foundation yesterday,
Alan Pike writes.
That was an improvement on the previous year - when typical monthly giving
fell to Pounds 1.28 - but the figures disguise the fact that the most
philanthropic section of the population donated 'substantially less' while
small givers supplied a little more.
As a result, total public support for charity was unchanged last year at
between Pounds 3.5bn and Pounds 4.3bn.
The research, conducted for the foundation by Manchester University, shows
that 24 per cent of the population donate nothing, while most of the 76 per
cent of donors confine their support to relatively modest levels.
The government wants the voluntary sector to take over an increased range of
services from public agencies, but the survey shows strong support for
continued state provision. A total of 90 per cent of respondents agreed that
the government had a basic responsibility to take care of people, with 86
per cent saying that the government should help more and not rely on
charities.
Individual Giving and Volunteering in Britain. CAF, 48 Pembury Road,
Tonbridge, Kent TN9 2JD. Pounds 14.95.
</TEXT>
