<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / House buyers' confidence 'fragile'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INQUIRIES from prospective home buyers have risen but sales are taking a
long time to complete and many would-be purchasers pull out at the last
minute, according to a survey of more than 100 estate agents published
today.
The Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors' survey says: 'Despite
increasing levels of buyer interest across the country, we are still a long
way from any sustained improvement in the housing market.'
Many estate agents appealed to the government to extend the moratorium on
stamp duty. They fear that there will be a rush to beat the deadline of
August 19 when the temporary suspension of duty on house sales below Pounds
250,000 is due to end, after which sales may fall sharply.
Mr Peter Miller, housing spokesman for the institution, said: 'The upward
trend of improvement in the residential market is apparent. However, fears
regarding job security and local economic factors can easily knock the
fragile confidence of buyers. The high level of abortive sales is
manifestation of unease in the market.'
The institution said that a reduction in the number of repossessed homes for
sale had eased pressures on the market.
The survey asked estate agents in England and Wales whether house prices had
moved during the three months to the end of May. More than 73 per cent said
prices did not change, about a quarter said prices fell and 1.1 per cent
said prices rose.
</TEXT>
