<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Tory election win fails to lift retail spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALES on Britain's high streets were virtually flat last month, suggesting
that the Conservative general election victory failed to prompt a spending
boom.
The volume of retail sales rose a seasonally adjusted 0.3 per cent in May,
compared with April's 0.8 per cent month-on-month rise, when sales were
boosted because of Easter falling late.
Although last month's increase was the second consecutive monthly rise, the
three-monthly trends suggest that British consumers are still reluctant to
spend.
In the three months to May, sales fell by 0.1 per cent on the previous three
months and were down 0.3 per cent on the same period a year previously.
The figures from the Central Statistical Office add to evidence that retail
sales have yet to show a sustained recovery. Last week the Confederation of
British Industry's distributive trades survey painted a similar picture of
sluggish sales.
Most recent figures from the CSO show that sales by food retailers rose by
0.4 per cent in the latest three months, and sales by department stores by
0.6 per cent.
Sales of non-food items - including clothing, footwear and household goods -
were less encouraging, falling by 0.6 per cent in the three months to May
compared with the previous three-month period.
The British Retail Consortium, a trade group that claims to represent 90 per
cent of the retail industry, said May was a month in which sectors reacting
favourably to good weather did best.
The Treasury welcomed the figures, pointing out that sales in May were at
the highest level since November 1991.
Mr Gordon Brown, Labour's trade spokesman, said: 'Today's figures showing
flat retail sales confirm that the British economy is yet to experience the
promised Tory post-election boom.'
</TEXT>
