<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Foundation transactions 'ceased'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VADUZ, LIECHTENSTEIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR WERNER KEICHER, the sole council member of the Maxwell Foundation, said
yesterday that there had been no transactions through the foundation since
Mr Robert Maxwell's death in November. He also said that he had not been
paid for his services since then.
The Maxwell Foundation is the Liechtenstein vehicle that was used by Mr
Maxwell to control many of his interests.
Mr Keicher, a Liechtenstein lawyer, said the foundation's objectives were:
to support basic scientific and medical research; to promote lasting peace
in Israel; to support capable young entrepreneurs; to support education for
encouraging peace and ending racism; and to support non-profit institutions
in Liechtenstein.
He said the foundation, established in 1970, had probably distributed less
than Pounds 2m since he took over from his father as trustee in 1985. Of
this sum, Pounds 1.5m had gone to Leeds University.
He denied knowledge of written instructions from people governing the
foundation or its subsidiaries. He had had 'absolutely no contact' with Mr
Kevin Maxwell or other members of the family in connection with distributing
money, and often made decisions on donations himself.
Mr Keicher, however, appears to have tremendous power, which he now intends
to wield for the first time.
He called the foundation the 'grandmother' of the US companies Sphere and PH
(US), two companies outside the reach of administrators which are still
trading. The foundation owns Swico, which controls the other two companies.
He said he believed he had powers to appoint or dismiss directors, and to
help determine dividends and 'absolutely would not hesitate' to remove Mr
Kevin Maxwell from the board of these companies if 'it is necessary'.
He said he knew nothing of transactions through PH (US) and other companies
in recent months, and emphasised that he had seen his role and that of the
foundation as a holding function, not a management function.
Asked why he had become involved in a foundation associated with Mr Robert
Maxwell, he said: 'When you look back from today, it's another situation. Mr
Maxwell was one of the most wealthy men in Britain, with a big reputation .
. . Now it is different, with the knowledge we have today.'
</TEXT>
