<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Report prompts rethink of law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has agreed to consider changes to the Financial Services Act
in the light of the confidential report by Imro, the self-regulatory body
for the fund management industry, on supervision of the Maxwell companies.
But ministers have indicated that they will wait until they have seen not
only the report but the detailed assessment of it by the Securities and
Investments Board (SIB).
Mr Anthony Nelson, the economic secretary, also signalled yesterday that the
government was unlikely to try to arrange publication of the report as a
parliamentary paper, in order to deal with the legal difficulties that are
said to exist with publishing a full report.
In response to a question from Mr David Shaw, one of the Tory MPs leading
the parliamentary campaign on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners, Mr Nelson
said that Treasury officials were discussing with SIB 'the scope of SIB's
ability to publish reports within the powers transferred to them under the
act'.
The MPs believe criticism of some of the professional advisers to the
Maxwell companies will increase the prospect of help for the pensioners.
The Treasury is said to be considering arranging for publication of the
report's conclusions and findings.
It is also conscious of the need to maintain some broad consistency between
the extent of what is published about the supervision of Maxwell companies
and the report of the Bingham inquiry into BCCI.
MPs are pressing Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, to make a
formal approach to the Liechtenstein authorities to release information
about the Maxwell affair. A delegation of MPs saw officials at the Swiss
embassy, which acts in Liechtenstein's interests, and were told that
co-operation could only follow a formal request.
</TEXT>
