<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Court clears trustees to cut Maxwell pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRUSTEES of the Maxwell Communications works pension scheme were
yesterday given High Court permission to 'eke out' their available funds by
reducing the pensions of 3,640 pensioners to 31 per cent for the next five
years.
About 1,600 of the pensioners who are former employees of Mirror Group
Newspapers will have their pensions topped up by MGN - although no guarantee
has been given about how long that will continue.
The remaining pensions will be topped up, for an unspecified period, out of
the government's Pounds 2.5m stop-gap fund.
The court was told that it would take Pounds 1.8m of the fund to top up all
the works scheme pensions for a year.
Continuation of the payment by the trustees of 31 per cent of pensions could
be affected if the scheme were found to be in deficit to the common
investment fund - the pot into which Maxwell pension funds were put for
investment. The deficit might be as much as Pounds 11m.
The court also said that the trustees could cease paying the annual 3 per
cent pension increase required by the works scheme rules.
Miss Sarah Asplin, for the trustees, told Sir Donald Nicholls, the
Vice-Chancellor - senior Chancery Division judge - that it was discovered at
the end of last year that about Pounds 109m was missing from the works
scheme's funds.
Describing the trustees' proposal as a fair, reasonable and sensible interim
measure, Sir Donald said they should keep the situation under close review
and return to court if it changed.
</TEXT>
