<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Solicitors seek cash for training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOLICITORS' profession is in danger of becoming limited to those with
private means, the Law Society warned yesterday.
In a letter to Mr John Patten, education secretary, society president Mr
Philip Ely said the collapse of the discretionary grant system for students
on the profession's finals course amounted to a 'pre-qualification means
test'.
The College of Law said the proportion of its income from fees paid by
English and Welsh local education authorities had halved in two years.
Urging Mr Patten to require authorities to provide grants, Mr Ely said
trainees were further disadvantaged in that professional-qualification
courses have been excluded from new arrangements for tax relief on
vocational training.
</TEXT>
