<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Fresh fighting in Sarajevo holes UN plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FRAGILE ceasefire in the besieged Bosnian capital of Sarajevo collapsed
yesterday, dashing United Nations hopes of sending food and humanitarian aid
to the starving people of the city.
UN officials said the ceasefire ended at dawn after the city came under
fresh mortar and heavy bombardment from the surrounding hills, which are
held by Serb irregulars and Serbia's proxy Bosnian army.
Last night Serb irregulars were again pounding the city and its suburbs with
artillery, and the main government building was bombarded for several hours.
Street fighting moved towards the centre of Sarajevo as Serb irregulars and
Bosnian territorial defence units engaged in long and sustained battles for
control of parts of the city.
Eye witnesses reported that Serb irregulars had entered the suburb of
Dobrinja, near the airport and had taken many people from their apartments,
evidently to exchange them for captured Serb snipers.
A senior UN official in Belgrade, the Serbian capital, said it was too
dangerous for the UN to try to reopen Sarajevo airport for an airlift of
food and other supplies. He said a UN convoy that left Belgrade yesterday
morning with relief supplies was still blocked from entering Sarajevo.
'There is no water, no food, no electricity. There is no hope. There is only
fighting. We are being abandoned by the world community,' said Mr Ivan
Knezovic, a philosophy professor at Sarajevo university.
He said he was afraid that the Serb irregulars would eventually take
Sarajevo street by street, house by house.
UN officials had pinned great hopes on the ceasefire, as one of the last
chances to re-open the airport. Serb irregulars have blockaded the airport
for 11 weeks, preventing the city's 300,000 inhabitants from receiving any
food supplies.
'There is little chance now that Canadian troops will be sent to take over
control of the airport,' Mr Knezovic said.
The Serb irregulars, led by Mr Radovan Karadzic, and General Ratko Mladic,
agreed to a ceasefire last Sunday in the belief they could use a lull in the
fighting to consolidate their positions in the city and eventually divide
it. The Serb irregulars have repeatedly broken previous ceasefires.
But western diplomats said an agreement between Bosnian President Alija
Izetbegovic, and Croatian President Franjo Tudjman to form a military
alliance could have persuaded the Serb irregulars to abandon the Sarajevo
ceasefire.
</TEXT>
