<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Lloyd's may give up plan to bail out Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS TO set up a bailout fund to help those Lloyd's Names hardest hit by
recent losses are running into difficulties and may be abandoned.
An emergency meeting of the Lloyd's council, the market's governing body,
was held yesterday to discuss a number of possible schemes.
The council will make an announcement today, and some form of help for
stricken Names is not entirely ruled out. However, a Lloyd's official
admitted that a bailout plan was 'looking less and less likely'.
The purpose of a bailout would be to cap the losses of those Names - the
individuals whose assets support underwriting - who have been worst affected
by Lloyd's recent losses. These are forecast to reach Pounds 2bn in the 1989
underwriting year. In line with Lloyd's three-year accounting system, these
figures will be announced next week. Officials working on the scheme are
understood to have been unable so far to solve complex legal and practical
difficulties.
A minority of the market's Names, who are members of 'spiral' reinsurance
syndicates - which provided high-level catastrophe cover to other syndicates
and companies - face a disproportionate share of losses.
Chatset, the company which tracks the results of Lloyd's syndicates, says
that Names on just 15 of the 401 syndicates trading could face losses of
Pounds 948m.
Any decision not to help them would be bound to stir controversy ahead of
the society's annual meeting next week.
Mr Christopher Stockwell, the chairman of the Lloyd's Names Associations
working party, warned that the market's crisis could deepen if no help was
offered. He predicted an 'an enormous wave of litigation' by Names in the
autumn.
'The council may duck the issue but our basic belief and expectation is that
something has to be done. Failure is the end of Lloyd's,' he added.
The idea of a bailout plan has had a chequered history over recent months.
In January, a task force under the chairmanship of Mr David Rowland,
chairman of international broker Sedgwick, recommended against retrospective
aid for Names, restricting its proposed cap on losses for future years. In
April, Mr David Coleridge, chairman, revived the idea of offering help to
the market's 'walking wounded' and a council sub-committee has examined
various options over the past two months.
Although the idea has found favour among some sections of the market,
neither agents nor brokers have been enthusiastic about contributing funds
to a scheme.
The mood among underwriters and agents at the Lloyd's market has shifted in
the past few weeks against setting up such a fund. This change of mood
follows the approval of plans to boost the size of Lloyd's central fund,
which meets losses when Names cannot pay claims.
</TEXT>
