<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / NY Daily News 'was conduit for funds'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR KEVIN MAXWELL is alleged to have used the New York Daily News as a
conduit to transfer funds from Maxwell companies in London to banks and
companies around the world.
According to newly obtained court documents filed by the Daily News, the
transactions were outside 'the ordinary course' of the newspaper's business.
The newspaper, bought by Mr Robert Maxwell in March 1991, has named Mr
Maxwell's son Kevin as having 'authorised and directed' the fund transfers
between March 21, 1991 and November 29, 1991.
The other person named as directing the transfers was Mr Robert Maxwell
himself, who died on November 5 last year.
The issue of the fund transfers is the subject of a legal dispute in the US
between the Daily News and other parties, including Mirror Group Newspapers
of the UK. MGN was floated in the UK by the Maxwell empire last May.
The Daily News court submission was made in answer to a question about its
financial affairs by the New York bankruptcy court. The newspaper filed for
bankruptcy protection last December.
The submission alleges that, from March to November 1991, the UK funds were
received by the Daily News 'and transferred to various entities in virtually
simultaneous transactions'.
The Daily News added that the funds served 'no business purpose' of their
own and that the newspaper was 'utilised merely as a conduit by Robert
Maxwell or his affiliated companies or family members for such transfers'.
The Daily News is itself being accused in the US court of aiding and
abetting a conspiracy to defraud MGN of Pounds 50m.
The Daily News, which has denied any wrongdoing, faces claims from MGN and
from the UK administrators of the Maxwell private companies for a total of
more than Dollars 200m (Pounds 110m) of Maxwell fund transfers.
This money came to the Daily News from both private and public Maxwell
companies in the UK and elsewhere.
It was learnt last night that Britain's Serious Fraud Office is
investigating a Pounds 50m transfer from MGN to the Daily News that occurred
on October 21, 1991.
Court documents filed by MGN this week in the US concerning the Pounds 50m
transfer accuse the Daily News of being liable for fraud, aiding and
abetting conspiracy to defraud and aiding and abetting MGN directors in a
breach of their fiduciary duties.
The court filing also asserts that both Mr Robert Maxwell and Mr Michael
Stoney, the former deputy MGN managing director in charge of finance, were
responsible for the misappropriation of MGN funds and a violation of their
fiduciary duties to MGN.
The filing also says that Mr Stoney drew down the Pounds 50m - which was
borrowed by MGN from the London office of Bankers Trust - upon the orders of
Mr Robert Maxwell.
Mr Stoney was moved by Mr Robert Maxwell to MGN in the spring of 1991.
</TEXT>
