FT  18 JUN 92 / International Company News: Air Canada to sell five cargo
aircraft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AIR CANADA has put its five DC-8 cargo aircraft up for sale as part of
efforts to rationalise its cargo operations, writes Robert Gibbens in
Montreal.
Air Canada has failed to make its key domestic cargo operations profitable,
partly because of the long recession. The airline saw overall cargo revenues
slip to CDollars 354m (USDollars 297m) in 1991 from CDollars 413m in the
previous year.
Air Canada said it was selling the DC-8s to reduce debt and bring unit costs
in line with other big carriers.
The five aircraft, which were used in Canada, are expected to fetch between
USDollars 125m and USDollars 130m and should find a receptive market.
Total cargo capacity will not change greatly after the sale because Air
Canada this spring brought three new 747-400 combination passenger-cargo
aircraft into service on its international routes.
Air Canada also plans to sell its credit card operation for about CDollars
300m.
Moody's Investors Service, the US rating agency, has placed under review
USDollars 1.5bn of Canadian Pacific long-term senior unsecured debt.
The move came after Unitel, CanPac's 60 per cent-owned subsidiary, won
regulatory permission to compete against Bell Canada in the domestic
long-distance telecommunications market.
Moody's said Unitel would face a financing requirement of USDollars 2.5bn
over the long term to compete effectively.
