<DATE>920618
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Political Notebook: Less heat, some light
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAYS OF light have begun to replace some of the intense heat in the
Conservative party generated by the Maastricht accords.
Mr John Major's return from Rio has prompted more sober reflection among
potential rebels on the wisdom of denigrating an agreement once hailed as a
personal triumph for their leader.
The more precocious of the new intake of Tory MPs have been reminded by the
party whips of how dull life on the back benches can become after 10 or 15
years.
The two dozen or so hardened Euro-sceptics have not changed their minds.
They never will. But many of those who happily signed up to last week's
synthetic rebellion are having second thoughts.
Of course it may not last. If the Irish vote against, there will be no
shortage of Tories ready to dance on the grave of the deal struck by their
prime minister.
Mr Major will be faced then with rebuilding from scratch the fragile
complexes of compromises with his own party and with Britain's European
partners he constructed after Margaret Thatcher's downfall.
There would be no certainty that he could again reconcile the federalist
ambitions of European colleagues with the instinctive nationalism of his
party.
Whichever way the Irish vote goes, the Tory anti-federalists at Westminster
will make mischief when Mr Major acquiesces in the reappointment of Mr
Jacques Delors at the Lisbon summit.
But if the Irish forsake the Danish option, Mr Major will be able to ride
out such turbulence. He will win a breathing space to map out a strategy for
the British presidency to restore his grip on his party without risking his
claim to have returned Britain to the heart of Europe.
His starting point remains that Britain is better off with the Maastricht
accords than without them.
Ministers do not really believe their public claims that the accords
represented a triumph for decentralisation over federalism. Their private
assessment is that Maastricht was a draw - that Britain managed to defer
until the next conference in 1996 the most difficult arguments about the
distribution of power within the community. But Mr Major bought time.
The choice he managed to finesse in December - was Britain's place at the
core or on the periphery of Europe? - would return with a vengeance if
Maastricht collapsed.
Ironically, Mr Norman Lamont, one of the Cabinet's less committed Europeans,
would be among those with most to lose. For a day or two, the chancellor
appeared to be quietly celebrating the Danish result. Now he is more
circumspect.
It is perhaps no accident that the apparent change of heart coincides with a
worrying Whitehall assessment of the possible Franco-German reaction to the
collapse of EMU.
What, some ministers are asking, would Britain do if Paris persuaded Bonn
and the others among the original six to bypass formal treaty changes by
simply locking irrevocably their exchange rates in the ERM?
Mr Lamont could keep sterling outside such a fixed system but he would pay a
high price in terms of British interest rates and the pace of economic
recovery.
The stark choices would not be confined to EMU. The collapse of the treaty
on political union might undermine decisively efforts to ensure that
Franco-German plans for a joint military force do not detach Europe from the
US.
So, Ireland permitting, Mr Major intends to press on with efforts to bring
Denmark back into the fold. There will be no rush to a confrontation with
Tory doubters. Ministers now refer to ratification during the first half of
next year - during the Danish presidency.
But Mr Major's hope is that the formula to change Danish minds could have
the same effect on Tory doubters.
The talk is of addenda to Maastricht that would commit the 12 not only to a
much tighter definition of Community responsibilities and to more
intergovernmental co-operation but also to an acceleration of preparations
for enlargement.
There is much that could go wrong even if the the Irish endorse the
treaties. But his strong track record suggests that Mr Major has a fighting
chance of persuading his party that by staying on the inside he can come up
with a deal that is good enough for the Danes and even better for the
Tories.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
