<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Move on Scots bankruptcies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONALISATION was being used by the government to derail a 'gravy train'
that had provided millions of pounds for Scottish accountants engaged in
insolvency cases, Mr Donald Dewar, shadow Scottish secretary, told the
Commons last night.
Mr Dewar supported provisions in the Bankruptcy (Scotland) bill to save
taxpayers' money by expanding the role of a public official - the Accountant
in Bankruptcy - to give a cost-effective sequestration service in Scotland.
During an earlier discussion on the bill, Mr Dewar stated that in 1991
Pannell Kerr and Forster of Glasgow received sequestration fees totaling
Pounds 3.427m, Ernst &amp; Young Pounds 2.2m, and Cork Gully Pounds 1.9m.
Underlining the need to change the existing system Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish
secretary, said the cost to the taxpayer of financing the administration of
individual sequestrations had risen from Pounds 13,000 in 1986 to Pounds
18.5m in 1991.
The expenditure was accounted for by the payment of fees and outlays of the
private-sector insolvency practitioners who undertook the work.
Mr Lang estimated that if the historical trends in the volume and costs of
sequestrations continued the expenditure would rise to some Pounds 50m by
1993-94 and over Pounds 80m by 1994-95.
He said the level of insolvency in Scotland on a per-capita basis had
changed from being broadly equivalent to the level in England and Wales in
1987 to some three times that level by 1990. Mr Lang insisted that the
change could not be explained through relative economic prosperity or
economic performance.
</TEXT>
