<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Supervisors are 'underestimated'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGERS are confused about what supervisors do and frequently underestimate
their competence, the UK body responsible for setting standards in
management training said yesterday
The Management Charter Initiative disclosed the finding at the launch of the
first national standards outlining best practice for supervisors.
Earlier this month, the Confederation of British Industry published research
showing that supervisors themselves are confused about their jobs. The new
finding adds to general concern at the performance of UK supervisors
compared with their counterparts in Germany and elsewhere. The UK's 1.2m
supervisors have a significant effect on business productivity.
The MCI discovered the confusion, which stems from poor communication
between the two tiers, during trials of the new standards conducted at 200
organisations from every sector of the economy.
