<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / Family companies shine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHARES of family-controlled listed companies have outperformed the
Financial Times All-Share Index by 30 per cent during the past 21 years,
according to a survey published today by accountants Stoy Hayward.
A Pounds 1 investment in 1970 in the 71 family companies in the survey would
have grown to Pounds 11.11 by 1991 compared with Pounds 8.72 for an
investment in the All-Share Index.
Controlling family shareholders attributed that better performance to their
ability to pursue consistent management objectives and take a long-term
view. Family companies were less vulnerable to takeover bids and under less
pressure to deliver short-term returns.
Family businesses were defined as those where a family or family interests
controlled 25 per cent of ordinary shares, but companies dominated by one
individual were excluded. Three quarters of British companies are
family-controlled.
More than 40 per cent of the family companies surveyed achieved a more than
10-fold rise in their share price while seven companies achieved a 50-fold
increase.
Companies in which a family owned more than 40 per cent performed less well
than those where the holding was smaller, the survey found.
Family Business Index. Stoy Hayward, 8 Baker St, London W1M 1DA. Free.
</TEXT>
