<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Liquidator sets up probe into affairs of Bristol-based bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD, ANDREW JACK and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTS of Deacon Hoare &amp; Co, a small Bristol-based bank which went
into liquidation last week, are being investigated for possible
irregularities, its liquidator said yesterday.
Mr Peter Rilett, the liquidator appointed by the court from Peat Marwick's
Bristol office, confirmed last night that he was examining movements of
money from the bank into other companies which shared some directors.
'There are matters which require to be investigated but until the
investigation is complete, I cannot say more,' said Mr Rilett. 'Among the
matters to be investigated are transactions with related parties, some with
related companies, a number of which are now in liquidation.'
Three smaller companies with related directorships are also now in
liquidation or receivership. They include Regent Leasing and Mistral
Finance.
Deacon Hoare's main directors were listed in its most recent accounts as Mr
Peter Garner of Bath and Mr Peter Tucker of Churt in Surrey. Mr Garner,
whose wife Anne is a former director of the company, owned 86 per cent of
Deacon Hoare's shares in 1990, with Mr Tucker owning most of the remainder.
Deacon Hoare, one of the smallest UK institutions with a banking licence,
applied for voluntary liquidation after its directors were informed that its
liabilities exceeded its assets. It is understood that the Bank of England
is aware of the position at Deacon Hoare. The bank provided leasing finance
for offices and motor vehicles, a line of business which has been badly hit
by the recession. A series of defaults on leasing agreements was blamed when
it decided to go into liquidation.
Deacon Hoare had fewer than 10 staff and around 200 depositors. Most
balances are believed to be below Pounds 20,000, the ceiling for eligibility
to recover up to 75 per cent of savings under the Deposit Protection Board
scheme.
Deacon Hoare offered unusually high interest rates to savers. According to
league tables prepared by Blay's Guides, a financial research company
followed throughout the industry - and published in magazines and newspapers
including the Financial Times - it offered the highest rate on Tax Exempt
Special Saver Accounts (Tessas) in the months following their introduction
last year.
On February 9 1991, for example, Deacon Hoare's Tessa offered 15.87 per
cent. The next highest rate, out of more than 110 accounts on offer, was
15.5 per cent. The average was below 14 per cent.
Representatives of at least one large life assurance company guided clients
towards Deacon Hoare on the basis of these high rates in spite of warnings
from consumer groups that unusually high interest rates usually reflect
greater risk.
An individual who invested the permitted maximum in a Deacon Hoare Tessa in
the first two years would have put in Pounds 4,800, not including accrued
interest.
</TEXT>
