<TEXT>
A BETTER than expected PSBR figure, coupled with a view that recent falls
had been overdone, boosted activity in stock index futures, writes Joel
Kibazo.
The squeeze on Monday in after-hours' trading was repeated early yesterday
and the June contract opened strongly at 2,601, pulling the underlying cash
market higher, and helping the contract establish a five-point premium to
cash. Light selling then caused a slight retreat and June traded at a
discount to fair value just before 11.30am.
June found further support from the favourable performance of gilts and
bonds and resumed its upward direction in the afternoon session, before
settling into a narrow four-point range. It closed at 2,620, just off the
day's high of 2,622 and up 27 from Monday's poor close and at a five-point
premium to cash. With the expiry of June later this week, fair value stands
at nil. Turnover reached 7,260 lots.
The day in the options market was extremely poor and turnover reached a
meagre 24,396 contracts, of which the FT-SE option traded a day's total of
10,905 lots.
Hanson was the busiest stock option, trading 1,454 lots, with the August 200
puts particularly active. This was followed by BAT, in which 1,000 lots were
dealt.
