<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Money Markets: Rates unchanged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SHORT-TERM rates in the sterling cash market were mostly unchanged
yesterday, even though the Bank of England forecast a shortage in the
morning that was smaller than dealers had expected.
Rates remained unchanged because the shortage, initially forecast at Pounds
700m, proved difficult to remove. Many of the Bank of England's previous
repurchase agreements are expiring this week, and the end of the second
quarter is also approaching. As a result, many market practitioners require
short-dated paper on their books for liquidity purposes.
The authorities are unwilling to offer the short-dated repurchase agreements
that the market would like, however, perhaps out of fear that this might
misrepresent their policy on base rates. Instead the Bank continued Monday's
practice of offering to buy the shorter dated Bands 1 and 2 at 9 7/8 per
cent, Band 3 at 9 21/32 per cent and Band 4 at 9 19/32 per cent.
Yesterday, the Bank bought Pounds 15m of Band 3 bank bills and Pounds 1m of
Band 4 bank bills in the early round. Later, it purchased Pounds 13m of Band
1 bank bills, Pounds 37m of Band 3 bank bills and Pounds 5m of Band 4 bank
bills. The forecast was revised down to around Pounds 550m at the start of
the afternoon. The Bank bought Pounds 4m of Band 1 treasury bills and Pounds
257m of Band 1 bank bills, and provided late assistance of around Pounds
80m.
One discount house trader said the Bank may have misjudged how 'sticky' the
market still was when revising down the shortage so much in the afternoon.
The overnight rate was still up at 11 1/2 per cent towards the end of
trading. One-week sterling libor ended firmer at 10 1/2 per cent, one-month
money stayed at 10 1/16 per cent and 3-month money closed at 10 per cent.
Trading in sterling futures had a more bullish tone, possibly because the
market was influenced by suggestions in two tabloid newspapers that the
British prime minister was considering an early cut in base rates. September
short sterling traded up 9 ticks to close at 90.25.
December short sterling also traded up 9 ticks to end at 90.54. Both
movements suggest that the market is back to believing there could be a
half-point cut in base rates before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
