FT  17 JUN 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: LME zinc price fall accelerates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Commodities Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FALL in zinc prices triggered by the London Metal Exchange's move on
Monday to ease a market squeeze accelerated yesterday, and traders and
analysts expect further losses in coming weeks, writes Our Commodities
Staff.
After watching the cash premium over three months metal climb from zero to
nearly Dollars 190 a tonne in two-and-a-half months the exchange stepped in
to establish maximum daily premiums for the June/July period, ranging from
Dollars 15 to Dollars 5 a tonne. A cash premium is normally associated with
supply tightness, but the recent widening of the price gap has been
coincided with a rapid build up in the exchange's warehouse stocks to a
record level.
The immediate response to the LME's action on Monday was a Dollars 24 fall
in the cash price and a narrowing of the 'backwardation', as the cash
premium is known, to Dollars 166 a tonne. Yesterday the cash price lost
another Dollars 56 at Dollars 1,367.50 a tonne and the backwardation shrank
further to Dollars 136.25.
'We're seeing signs of liquidation - it (the three months price) has gone
through the Dollars 1,250 support without too much difficulty,' commented
independent metals analyst Mr Robin Bhar.
'When you are a manufacturer it is difficult to appreciate what seems to be
a game, and a highly expensive one at that,' one producer said.
