FT  17 JUN 92 / International Company News: Central Capital wins protection
from creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CENTRAL Capital, the Canadian financial services group which includes the
country's fourth-largest trust company, has been granted court protection
from 39 senior unsecured creditors, writes Robert Gibbens in Montreal.
An Ontario court froze all other claims against Central Capital under the
federal Companies Creditors Arrangement Act and appointed Peat Marwick
Thorne as administrator.
The 39 creditors, led by the Royal Bank of Canada which is owed CDollars
550m (USDollars 462m), will ask for a supervised restructuring of Central
Capital, transferring its mortgage insurance and general insurance arms to
the creditors.
Central Capital owes a total of about CDollars 1.7bn. Its 80 per cent-owned
trust subsidiary is in the process of being sold.
Mr Bill Woloshyn, a lawyer for Royal Bank of Canada, said the creditors
wanted to secure maximum recovery and ensure that a restructured Central
Capital can survive.
