<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tower in US S&amp;L Maxwell connection
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ROBERT MAXWELL used former Senator John Tower to seek US government
assistance for an aborted attempt in 1988 to acquire 15 insolvent Texas
savings-and-loans institutions, according to a former US bank regulatory
official.
Tower, who died in an air crash last year, was a paid consultant to Maxwell
and served on the board of Macmillan, the publisher owned by Maxwell
Communication Corporation (MCC).
In August 1988 Senator Tower went to see Mr Danny Wall, then chairman of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the now-defunct agency that previously
regulated the US savings-and-loan industry.
The former Texan Senator met Mr Wall to argue on behalf of a bid by Maxwell
for 15 failing savings-and-loan institutions that were later declared
insolvent, sold as a single package and renamed the Bluebonnet Savings Bank.
A Congressional investigator claimed at the weekend that 'Maxwell hired
Tower to try and grease the savings-and-loan deal', but Mr Wall, who
resigned in March 1990, said he saw 'nothing nefarious' in Tower's approach.
</TEXT>
