<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM warns schools on standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCHOOLS that perform poorly will face a choice between being helped to
improve by teams of teachers coming in from outside, or being shut down, Mr
John Major signalled yesterday.
In his first post-election address on domestic policies, the prime minister
also made clear that his desire to see change in the social agenda included
housing and law and order, and was not confined to the higher-profile areas
of education and health.
That development of his campaign themes of the 'right to own, the power to
choose' came in a speech last night to the Adam Smith Institute, the
free-market think tank.
In a look ahead to the white paper on schools which is due to be published
later in the summer, Mr Major promised radical proposals for schools -
particularly in inner cities - where the independent inspectorate of schools
found standards were far too low.
'I do not believe that government can stand indefinitely by. If the
governors or the local authority are unwilling or unable to put things
right, then we must find ways to raise standards for the children in them,'
he said.
Drawing on his own experiences, as he did increasingly in his campaign
speeches, Mr Major recalled his childhood among people who did not have much
money but who still wanted to be independent, and said that the task for the
1990s was to widen the avenue of choice. 'We mean to empower not just the
enterprising, but all people - the least well off  - those most dependent on
public services as well.'
In a scarcely veiled reference to the tone of some Tory rhetoric of the
1980s, the prime minister emphasised his view that reform had to start at
the top, and that if people did feel dependent that was the fault of
government and others in authority who arrogantly behaved as if they knew
best.
'I don't want to hear any more carping about the faults of the dependent,'
he said. Government had made people dependent 'not because we provide the
welfare and the services, but by denying people the basic human dignity of
independent choice in the way they are provided'.
While education and health were at the forefront of the Tory election
campaign emphasis on extending choice and opportunity, Mr Major's speech
highlighted the need to extend further the government's plans to bring more
choice into home ownership and into the public and private rented sectors.
He said that the government wanted policing that would be more responsive to
public concerns.
</TEXT>
