<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont takes tough line on interest
rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT last night flatly rejected calls from some Conservative MPs
for an immediate cut in interest rates to speed up the pace of economic
recovery.
In a tough speech to members of the Conservative backbench finance
committee, the chancellor also insisted that there could be no question of
any devaluation of sterling within the European Exchange Rate Mechanism.
Responding to disquiet among many Tory MPs that the April election victory
has not brought the promised recovery, Mr Lamont appeared to acknowledge
that the Treasury had downgraded its growth forecasts for this year.
MPs at the meeting said that he had left the impression that the economy was
likely to be flat this year rather than growing by the 1 per cent predicted
in his March budget. But Mr Lamont sought to quash speculation that he is
under pressure from the prime minister and cabinet colleagues to 'kick
start' the economy with an early cut in interest rates.
He told the MPs that the government had refused to 'play politics' with the
economy in spite of the pressures it faced in the run-up to the general
election. To take a short-term view now would be entirely illogical and
would risk the medium-term rewards promised by the present tough stance
against inflation.
He warned also that such determination to judge the economy's performance
over a period of years rather than months would mean tough constraints on
key public-spending programmes during the present round of Whitehall
negotiations.
In spite of his reputation as the cabinet's most important Euro-sceptic, Mr
Lamont was careful not to support calls from some MPs for the government to
abandon the goal of a single currency enshrined in the threatened Maastricht
treaty. He told the meeting that the Danish vote against the treaty called
for a period of 'cool reflection' but highlighted the benefits of the ERM
and the potential gains from a single currency.
</TEXT>
