FT  17 JUN 92 / NHS accused of race discrimination
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Health Service has been accused by the Commission for Racial
Equality of discriminating against ethnic-minority nurses by putting them on
lower pay grades than other NHS workers.
At the same time, the CRE has announced it is to investigate whether
ethnic-minority doctors get the same opportunities when they apply for top
NHS jobs as their white colleagues.
A shake-up of pay for all nurses, midwives and health visitors with clinical
responsibilities took place in 1988.
All jobs were evaluated and new grades were drawn up. More than 137,000
nurses - a quarter of the workforce - have lodged appeals against the grades
awarded to them.
When the regrading exercise was launched, no one in the health service
considered the possibility of racial discrimination and no attempt was made
to monitor by ethnic origin, the results of regrading the CRE said. Yet the
nature of the regrading meant that 'there was ample opportunity for local
managers to treat staff unfavourably on racial grounds'. Those in nurse
management were relatively inexperienced in their personnel functions and
key staff were given very little training in job evaluation, the CRE found.
It reports union allegations that many nursing auxiliaries and enrolled
nurses - among whom ethnic minorities are disproportionately represented -
were automatically placed in the lowest grades, without any attempt to
assess the work they were doing.
The CRE said it was impossible to gauge how many nurses had suffered
discrimination during the regrading - 20 race complaints had been registered
with industrial tribunals - but that was likely to be only the surface of
the problem, it said.
On top jobs for doctors, the commission said there had been several
successful complaints by ethnic minority doctors to industrial tribunals.
The Health Department was unable to comment.
</TEXT>
