<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Guinness judge offers trials plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GUINNESS trial judge who called for a solution to long fraud trials has
produced his own radical and controversial proposals.
Speaking publicly last night for the first time since the trial of former
merchant bankers Mr Roger Seelig and Lord Spens was stopped in February, Mr
Justice Henry said parliament should oblige defendants to detail their
defences before the trial.
He argued that the judge and not the prosecutor should make the opening
statement in a trial, giving the jury an impartial indication of the various
issues involved.
A defendant would be more ready to give advance details of his defence if he
knew that his side of the story would be indicated to the jury at the outset
of the proceedings.
Parliament might need to impose time limits on jury trials. Save in
exceptional cases, four months should be long enough, Mr Justice Henry said.
He also argued in favour of keeping juries in serious fraud trials.
Giving the Child &amp; Co Lecture at the Council of Legal Education, the judge
said: 'The competence of the criminal law to deal with serious fraud is
clearly crucial today when the power-driven, greed-fed, dishonest excesses
of the 1980s have not proved to be the end of an unfortunate era but an
introduction to worse since.
'We have to be able to deal with serious fraud: to deter it, to detect it,
and to punish it.
'We must do this to protect the creditors, employees, and shareholders of
limited liability companies.
'We must do this to protect the public, whose pensions and insurances depend
on it. We must do this to protect the integrity of the market.'
Serious fraud trials took too long, were insufficiently focused on the real
issues, cost too much and placed too great a strain on those involved, he
said.
Advocating the retention of juries, he said the great majority of judges who
had tried long fraud cases had come through confident in their jury and in
the verdicts they would give.
Equal justice in cases of white-collar crime as in blue-collar crime was one
reason for keeping the jury, he said.
Juries needed more help, though. 'It seems to me there is a case for the
trial judge opening both the law and the issues to the jury. This would
require him to summarise each defendant's case.'
He would also like to be able to give the jury his own running summaries of
the evidence on each issue.
</TEXT>
