<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Economists fear record PSBR total
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUBLIC-SECTOR finances deteriorated by less than expected last month, but
economists warned that Britain was still heading for a record deficit this
financial year.
The public-sector borrowing requirement in May was Pounds 3.1bn, including
privatisation proceeds of Pounds 0.8bn. That brought the cumulative PSBR
total since April - the beginning of the financial year - to Pounds 6.6bn,
compared with Pounds 5.6bn in the same period last year.
Mr James Barty, UK economist at investment bank Morgan Grenfell, said: 'The
two monthly figures we have had so far are on the whole consistent with a
PSBR of around Pounds 32bn.'
In the March Budget Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, forecast a PSBR of
Pounds 28bn, double the size of the previous year's deficit. With any
economic upturn this year likely to be weak, the Treasury's figure is likely
to be exceeded as tax receipts fail to live up to expectations and high
unemployment keeps government spending high.
Total cash receipts in May were Pounds 15.2bn and Pounds 32.1bn for the
first two months of 1992-93, 2 per cent lower than the Pounds 32.8bn of
receipts in the first two months of the previous financial year. Inland
Revenue receipts in April and May were 4.5 per cent lower than a year
earlier at Pounds 11.4bn.
The Treasury said income tax collected to date this year had been boosted by
the payment of bonuses before the general election to avoid planned tax
increases by a Labour government.
According to Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist at investment bank Salomon
Brothers, the month's figures were also cushioned by prompt receipt of poll
tax payments.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
