<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Botnar's business 'lacked rules'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN UK, the former importer-distributor of Nissan vehicles controlled by
Mr Octav Botnar, was run in 'an unconventional and extraordinary way', the
High Court was told yesterday.
Mr Anthony Boswood QC, counsel for Nissan UK, said 'there was a complete
lack of 'proper' formalities, rules, procedures and lines of reporting such
as one would expect to find in a business of such size and importance.'
Mr Boswood was summing up for Nissan UK, which is being sued for more than
Pounds 1m in damages by Mr Stan Cholaj, a former assistant managing director
of the company who is claiming wrongful dismissal and breach of contract.
Mr Boswood said that Mr Botnar controlled the company in an autocratic way.
'Mr Botnar treated this company as his own personal thing or fiefdom,' he
said.
The hearing continues today.
</TEXT>
