<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Conflict between roles and masters led to confusion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EARLY in 1972, some of the most powerful men in Britain
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
trade union leaders, civil servants, businessmen and politicians - met
regularly amid great secrecy to plot the nation's economic future.
They drew up secret national economic plans that paved the way for the
voluntary incomes policy that the Heath government introduced in late 1972.
They met at the offices of the National Economic Development Office. A
former senior Nedo economist who sat in on the sessions recalls: 'We tried
to agree on the rate of profit which would be required to finance the
investment needed to increase productivity by enough to finance the unions'
real wage claims.'
It was the closest Nedo got to combining its many roles into real power. It
was also indicative of one of the weaknesses that has dogged Nedo from its
birth in early 1962 to yesterday's announcement that it is to be disbanded:
the confusion between its different roles and masters.
Nedo was created by Mr Harold Macmillan's Tory government in 1962 as an
attempt to mimic the apparent success of indicative planning in the post-war
rebuilding of French industry.
The unemployment of the 1930s had persuaded him that co-operation between
government, industry and unions was essential for economic growth. Nedo was
intended to create that co-operation.
Harold Wilson's Department of Economic Affairs, which was responsible for
economic planning and was intended as a counterweight to the Treasury, was
substantially staffed by Nedo officials. After Labour's brief but
unsuccessful experiment with planning in the mid 1960s, Nedo became a feeble
instrument of incomes policy and industrial strategy in the 1970s. In the
1980s it withered under the ideological onslaught of the Thatcher
government's attack on the corporate state.
Nedo's performance has to be assessed against its various roles.
Planning: Nedo was established when French planning was already becoming
less effective and it lacked many of the tools that French experience
suggested were needed for planning. Nedo was discredited by the failure of
Labour's national economic plan in the mid 1960s.
Economic policy: After the voluntary incomes policy of 1972, Nedo was a
largely ineffective forum for agreeing and policing incomes policy deals. In
the 1980s, the unions lost much of their power, companies decentralised
bargaining and the growth of the service sector made national industrial
bargaining less relevant.
Industrial strategy: The Labour industrial strategy between 1976 and 1979
gave Nedo new life, exploring the supply side of the economy and British
industrial competitiveness. Former Nedo officials say much of the work was
overblown special pleading by sectional interests. But many of the so-called
'little Neddies', which will be retained under the DTI's umbrella, did
useful work on grassroots issues of competitiveness.
Information: Nedo's most consistently useful role has been as an independent
assessor of the health of the British economy. Its highly influential report
on value added tax in 1965 was followed by extensive and critical reports on
the nationalised industries in the 1970s and the parlous state of training
in the 1980s.
On balance, Nedo was not a success across its 30-year life. It did not
succeed in its original aim of being the mechanism for public policy to
improve industrial competitiveness. It was better at small things - economic
reports and sectoral initiatives - than big things - planning and promoting
social co-operation.
Its weaknesses were a reflection of the institutions that were its parents.
The leadership of the TUC and the CBI could not persuade their members to
abide by agreements made at Nedo.
Most important, the central state was unwilling to devolve any of its power
over economic policy to an independent body. Nedo was always overshadowed by
the Treasury.
It was never a fully accepted part of the machinery of the state nor fully
outside it. It was deprived of influence over policy making on the inside
but never had the political independence it needed to produce radical ideas.
A former Nedo chief economist recalls his work: 'We spent a lot of time
inspecting a huge setting sun. We were dealing with an industrial decline
which was so deep-seated that we could do very little to arrest it. We
produced a lot of useful diagnoses of the problems, but we were not able to
do anything about them. We had no agenda to change British society.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
