<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / US Names continue action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW YORK lawyers acting for dissident US Names intend to appeal against a US
court decision dismissing part of their action against Lloyd's of London.
The case is the biggest of a series of actions brought by US Names who are
alleging that Lloyd's, the insurance market, breached US securities laws
when they were recruited.
On Monday, Judge Maurice Lasker dismissed proceedings brought by 91 Names
against 319 Lloyd's syndicates.
The US district court judge ruled that the action could not be brought
against the syndicates because they had no legal existence under English
law.
Syndicates are annual joint ventures, formed by Names, the individuals whose
capital supports underwriting on the Lloyd's market.
Ms Minna Schrag, of Prokauer Rose Goetz Mendelsohn, said the Names would
appeal. Action against three other classes of defendants - managing
agencies, members' agencies and Lloyd's itself - would continue.
Each defendant has filed separate motions to dismiss the action.
Although they are on a variety of legal grounds, all the defendants argue
that, under the member's contractual agreement with the agent, disputes
arising from membership should be heard under English law in an English
court.
</TEXT>
