<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 92 / Tribunal vindicates dismissed striker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NORTH sea oil worker sacked for striking was unfairly dismissed, an
industrial tribunal has ruled, Catherine Milton writes.
The tribunal, in Aberdeen, found that Mr James Byrne had been unfairly
dismissed because he lost his job for taking unofficial strike action in
1990 while Mr John Goddard, described as an 'agent provocateur', had been
kept on even though he had taken part in the action.
Lawyers for Wood Group Engineering, the employer, argued that Mr Byrne was
dismissed for disobeying lawful instructions to leave the oil rig, the site
of a sit-in, whereas Mr Goddard had returned to shore. Yesterday the company
said it was studying the result.
Mr Byrne was one of more than 700 oil workers dismissed after unofficial
strike action over recognition in 1990.
</TEXT>
